41, 27. vigorem ct constantiam et expertum . . . animum] rigorem, constantiam et, etc. — Α (Γ). This reading, though hitherto universally rejected, accords with the consistent practice of Tacitus in the use of et after an asyndeton, the third member being amplified and adding a new and often, as here, the most important clement in the enumeration. cp.
